    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2534176022" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2534176022" />
    <a title="Kelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8545345-kelly"><img alt="Kelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617558278p2/8545345.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2534176022?book_show_action=true">Sep 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly" href="/user/show/8545345-kelly">Kelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780755337446" href="/book/show/2211866.Truly_Madly_Yours">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8545345-kelly?shelf=romance-contemporary">romance-contemporary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2534176022" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16258929665205905668">Rachel Gibson novels are usually a sure win, but I really did not like &apos;Truly Madly Yours&apos;. I did not like the characters, I did not like the writing style, I did not enjoy myself at all. I do not like green eggs and ham. <br/><br/>First off, the hero was a prick and he didn&apos;t develop at all throughout the novel. He&apos;d been a little shit as a child, and he was a little shit as an adult. He was childish, sexually aggressive (not in any sort of good way) and darn mean. I really didn&apos;t understand if we were a</span>
  <span id="freeText16258929665205905668" style="display:none">Rachel Gibson novels are usually a sure win, but I really did not like 'Truly Madly Yours'. I did not like the characters, I did not like the writing style, I did not enjoy myself at all. I do not like green eggs and ham. <br /><br />First off, the hero was a prick and he didn't develop at all throughout the novel. He'd been a little shit as a child, and he was a little shit as an adult. He was childish, sexually aggressive (not in any sort of good way) and darn mean. I really didn't understand if we were actually supposed to like him?<br />Delaney was so bland that by the end of the week I won't remember her. She apparently had sarcasm and sass but for the most part she was as much of a whiner as Nick. <br /><br />There were barely any supporting characters that were given any real development so the focus was solely on Nick and Delaney, but the whole plot was super repetitive. They'd meet, they'd lash out at each other verbally, often saying really hurtful things, and then they'd get off with each other. And repeat. Somehow despite the mean words and teasing, they fell in love.<br /><br />My problem was that there were no real events in which you could see why they fell in love. Lust, maybe. But love? Nah. It wasn't like Nick had been a little shit as a kid but was now a respectable grown up who did grown up things and was clearly a nice guy. He still slept around, he still made cutting remarks, he didn't take no for an answer unless he was the one saying it… there was absolutely no romance in this novel at all.<br /><br />Similarly, there were no resolutions or developments. Delaney hated her Mother at the start of the book and they still hadn't developed beyond that point by the end. Nick's mother was stubborn and bitter, and she was still that way in the end. Delaney still hated Helen from childhood, and that still hadn't been sorted… <br /><br />I also found that too many elements were repeated but without impact. If I read about that fecking snowball story once more, I was going to throw the book in a very smelly bin in anger. Lets tell this impactless story from three points of view AND continue to have conversations about it in the meantime even though it happened like fifteen years ago!!<br /><br />Honestly, I'm not sure how I continued to read the whole novel, but it really was not one of Rachel Gibson's best novels, in fact it wasn't even okay as a regular romance novel either, regardless of the usually sterling reputation of the author.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16258929665205905668" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

