<div id="review_1233496067" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1233496067" />
    <a title="Anita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10765339-anita"><img alt="Anita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547669665p2/10765339.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1233496067?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anita" href="/user/show/10765339-anita">Anita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10765339-anita?shelf=romance">romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10765339-anita?shelf=kindle-la-city">kindle-la-city</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10765339-anita?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1233496067" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9198358542199130869">I haven&apos;t read much Rachel Gibson. Straight romance is not my favorite genre, but Rachel Gibson does it very well. I kept trying to turn it into a romantic-suspense in my mind. It would have made a great romantic-suspense book, the plot, the cast of characters, it would have been great. As a romance, it was really good. The problem with romance is you know how it will end. How it gets to that ending is the tension that keeps us all reading them. <br/><br/>Delaney is the adopted daughter of Henry Shaw, the</span>
  <span id="freeText9198358542199130869" style="display:none">I haven't read much Rachel Gibson. Straight romance is not my favorite genre, but Rachel Gibson does it very well. I kept trying to turn it into a romantic-suspense in my mind. It would have made a great romantic-suspense book, the plot, the cast of characters, it would have been great. As a romance, it was really good. The problem with romance is you know how it will end. How it gets to that ending is the tension that keeps us all reading them. <br /><br />Delaney is the adopted daughter of Henry Shaw, the area bigwig. She is also something of a free spirit and found her childhood very restrictive and took off at 19 to live her life and make her own decisions. Nick is the wild bastard child of Henry and has grown up with a pile of resentment for the Shaw family. He made Delaney scared for most of her childhood. Nick has a rep for being a love em and leave em type. Henry dies and his will sets up some very unusual conditions for two of the heirs, Delaney and Nick. The old man really knew how to exert control from beyond the grave. Delaney and Nick have a time of it trying to fight the attraction that has always been between them and when they lose, it is a very hot scene indeed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9198358542199130869" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


